<subSubSection id="78437FEBDCAB4EF615CBFE1D2C301BCB" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" type="notes">
<paragraph id="DCEE06DE39EC4901354357CC1FB7D236" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CEF3240C0D0A6B76EFA3170E7E603F59" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
This species is a native of south-eastern Australia, but introduced into many countries for utilisation purposes (mostly as an ornamental shrub). It easily reproduces and, like other acacias, is often considered to be an invasive species (
<bibRefCitation id="F0E3753C16220AA936E1155D75EE275F" author="Miller, J T" journalOrPublisher="Diversity and Distributions" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="848 - 860" refId="B6509274" refString="Miller, J T, Murphy, D J, Brown, G K, Richardson, D M, Gonzalez-Orozco, CE, 2011. The evolution and phylogenetic placement of invasive Australian Acacia species. Diversity and Distributions 17 (5): 848 - 860" title="The evolution and phylogenetic placement of invasive Australian Acacia species" volume="17" year="2011">Miller et al. 2011</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="18618DCF6AB9E4F5153F246B4EF3360A" author="Luque, GM" journalOrPublisher="Biological Invasions" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="981 - 985" refId="B6509222" refString="Luque, GM, Bellard, C, Bertelsmeier, C, Bonnaud, E, Genovesi, P, Simberloff, D, Courchamp, F, 2014. The 100th of the world's worst invasive alien species. Biological Invasions 16 (5): 981 - 985" title="The 100 th of the world's worst invasive alien species" volume="16" year="2014">Luque et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5344947D5C1BF906C453D2CD9B1ECD65" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
In Tenerife, 
<taxonomicName id="17791386175DF6ACAD6ABC00834FEEA4" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Cactaceae" genus="Acacia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Acacia dealbata" order="Cactales" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="dealbata">
<emphasis id="00EBA18688A7BF84C8F60C1E5ABCFBEB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Acacia dealbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a naturalised shrub, although some records doubtlessly refer to 
<taxonomicName id="223FF93669B7B87C0796E3B1660485A9" genus="A." lsidName="A. mearnsii" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" rank="species" species="mearnsii">
<emphasis id="29994693CD1446E58F39D09767F3E5FE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">A. mearnsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
instead. The latter superficially resembles 
<taxonomicName id="991814AAC80176DD14F1BB983C132089" genus="A." lsidName="A. dealbata" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" rank="species" species="dealbata">
<emphasis id="AF1E725156AB5AD4FAF28FF93704C8E2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">A. dealbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is recognised by its green and shiny foliage (vs. foliage bluish-grey with lustrous leaflets), cream flowers (vs. bright yellow flowers) (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="DBCD87E79CE4F30A4B05C84AC6BFF037" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F6510131" captionText="Figure 1. Acacia mearnsii, Tegueste, January 2019. Compared with A. dealbata, this species has a green, shiny foliage and cream flowers." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e62878.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/494334" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">1</figureCitation>
) and pods softly appressed grey-pubescent to velutinous (vs. pods glabrous). Furthermore, in 
<taxonomicName id="B05DD54DC4BFE03394543EE2730F77B3" genus="A." lsidName="A. dealbata" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" rank="species" species="dealbata">
<emphasis id="964C7C867D81DD99F683A85D11CE6A3D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">A. dealbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, there is only a single gland at the base of the pinnae, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="9A0097953607DDDF6B55377F7F45B1EA" genus="A." lsidName="A. mearnsii" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" rank="species" species="mearnsii">
<emphasis id="4685891BA77E013F647242BB7203A27E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">A. mearnsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
on at least some leaves, multiple glands are present between the pinnae (
<bibRefCitation id="EDCA8EE103C64BE5C8970713532554A8" author="Maslin, BR" journalOrPublisher="Plant Diversity" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="353 - 480" refId="B6509256" refString="Maslin, BR, Ho, BC, Sun, H, Bai, L, 2019. Revision of Senegalia in China, and notes on introduced species of Acacia, Acaciella, Senegalia and Vachellia (Leguminosae: Mimosoideae). Plant Diversity 41 (6): 353 - 480" title="Revision of Senegalia in China, and notes on introduced species of Acacia, Acaciella, Senegalia and Vachellia (Leguminosae: Mimosoideae)" volume="41" year="2019">Maslin et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="19DF265BF4F03486F757B4E9B9E7D48D" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
In Tegueste, 
<taxonomicName id="AF22B41767964E6C48774479E72A3CDA" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Cactaceae" genus="Acacia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Acacia mearnsii" order="Cactales" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="mearnsii">
<emphasis id="4DBE79D1A6EF093F2D50250C0429B204" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Acacia mearnsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was probably initially planted a long time ago and now survives. In the same place, a single individual was also observed of 
<taxonomicName id="BBE28C612A24B458FFDFC13B76A07454" genus="A." lsidName="A. decurrens" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" rank="species" species="decurrens">
<emphasis id="F15A2D59A38E75CE15E4611BB181B766" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">A. decurrens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see earlier).
</paragraph>
